The tenant of Bakal: The stoves are heating up, he has signed a higher rent.
An imposing elderly man came out through the door of the RPG Byty customer center of the "coal baron" Zdenek Bakal, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
He carried under his arm a file with three new rental contracts for three apartments: his own, that of his daughter and his son who is serving a sentence.
Deregulation has increased rent to these three people.
Instead of paying 3500 the son will have to pay from next year for a 2+1 apartment of second category 4100 crowns.
"And there is no hot water and the heating works with solid fuel," the man who has the power of signature is pointed out on his son's new contract.
"But I signed anyway," he explains, speaking in anger and half resigned.
The citizen association of apartments BytyOKD.cz which has described the new rental conditions as "immoral and indecent", advises tenants not to sign and wait until December 7, when will be published a notice to explain the method to follow to claim.
But the man reacts to this with a gesture of the hand.
"One says that, the other says something else" by frowning.
The Ostrava region becomes the laboratory of deregulation.
After the New Year, this is what awaits most of the apartments in the Czech Republic whose rents do not correspond to the market price.
Aktualne.cz decided to personally visit the "laboratory".
The RPG waiting room in Havirovska Street is one of four in the Ostrava region and it is already full on Tuesdays at 09 a.m.
Right next to the door stands a guard of a security company with a device to call customers.
A special button, "rent 2011", is on on the touch screen.
Only one pressure and a paper with a number comes out of the device.
You don't have time to read your "157" number that your number already starts to light up on the big screen under the top of the waiting room.
In a split second it's your turn.
After a short while, an old couple arrives to inquire about the rent, but the new rents do not seem to concern people in the waiting room.
The majority of people have come to solve common problems like everywhere - demand for repairs, insurance events and others.
In the Ostrava region, people from more than 44000 apartments in the RPG portfolio receive mail with the new lease agreements in their mailbox since about mid-November.
RPG Byty offers them rent increases of 15 to 38 percent.
The special window for new rents has been open to the public since November 18.
"it has been working for almost a week, so it's still on trial," replies, after a moment of hesitation, the employee behind the counter when the client introduces herself as a journalist.
The deragulation and old apartments of Bakal miners are a very sensitive local subject.
The vice-president of the parliament and from the region of Ostrava Lubomir Zaoralek of the Social Democrats mentioned this in a rather sustained way before the elections and this now fills the local newspapers.
"20 years after them, I want a new floor."
"They didn't even change me a put... in a board in the toilets, relieves himself in the introduction the man mentioned.
However, it is mostly, according to employees, retirees who come to be sure that they will receive a discount on the new rent price if they now sign as promised RPG in a special offer.
It is a discount of half the amount of the rent that will be received by the other tenants who have signed their new contract before December 15.
But the "deregulation" counter on Havirovaska Street is really not overwhelmed by the questions.
"Of the 360 customers who came yesterday, only 40 to 50 came for rent," says the employee at the counter.
And yet RPG poses both on its website and in the windows of individual interviews on rents when necessary.
If both parties do not agree on the rent, it is an independent court that will make the decision.
“These are not threats but only to inform about the unique and legitimate way of acting legally,” RPG said on its website.
"Here no one will go to court" thinks one of the employees of RPG Byty and the man in the street in front of the customer center is right.
"I have 13000 retirement crowns and I have 5000 crowns left to eat, I don't have enough to go to court," he said.
The employee suddenly feels uncomfortable.
"We'll see."
"Mr. Zaoralek in the media asks that no one sign and therefore people wait, "says she.
Rent regulation ends in the Czech Republic with the beginning of 2011 and increases, according to RPG Byty, are an economic necessity.
"And, in addition, the current rents still do not reach the level necessary for the simple maintenance of the fund for housing," recalls Pavel Klimes, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, that it is precisely the negligence of the fund for housing that makes the tenant angry is the main reason for the increase in rent.
However, in 5 years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able with rents to invest in apartments 4 billion, in four years from 2011 to 2014 this should make 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling in front of the upholstered armchairs in the waiting room on Havirosvka Street, however, repeats some information indicated in red.
“The increase in rent in 2011 is 15 percent and covers no less than 31200 apartments, or more than 90 percent of RPG apartments.”
"And it will always be at most 7,50 Czech crowns per m2 per month," the screen said.
The 38 percent increase is only for 400 apartments in the RPG portfolio.
"In these cases, it is an increase of a really very low sum 19.66 Czech crowns per m2," adds RPG.
Next year the rent will remain the same for 2600 apartments.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not cause a radical but gradual increase over 4 to 8 years.
It adds other commitments: all the money from the increase in rents (see the graph) is returned to the apartments in the form of heating savings - new windows and heating.
Those who sign the agreement on the rent increase have priority.
The nursery school is also part of the offices have included architects.
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the Arch company. Design.
No one could have expected it to also house a mini kindergarten with everything you need - color walls, imaginative furniture, toys and finally a miniature playground on the terrace.
Since October of last year, children of Arch. design employees have been going there.
The Archlectonic Projects Society Arch. Design. whose workshops have produced a large number of constructions in Brno, has imagined its mini corporate kindergarten since the first drafts of the Avriopoint building.
She employs about 90 people, especially the age to have children, and it was important to her that women architects and project managers could quickly return to work.
At the same time as reduced-time employment contracts, kindergarten is a bonus offered to its employees by the company Arch. Design. as part of its social program.
Builders and architects have the opportunity to combine work that takes care of children.
It was the employees of Arch.Design. themselves who imagined this kindergarten and with the support of the management they were able to obtain an endowment from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The mini kindergarten is financed by the European Social Fund through the operational programme of human resources and the State budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the financing allocations (up to 2.8 mil. of Czech crowns). They were able to purchase equipment and appliances and after two years insure qualified personnel as well as start-up.
After the use of the financing endowment (two years) the Arch company. Design. has the obligation after 3 years to operate the mini kindergarten on its own funds.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and it was Economy rating that helped to make the staffing request.
Child care is provided by qualified staff, all day long a nurse and kindergarten teacher take care of the children; children can go to kindergarten without age limit but they are over three years old for the most part.
As this is a "mini kindergarten" there can only be 5 children present at the same time, but during the day there are more who replace themselves.
The operation of the school is flexible according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use this school without regard to the hierarchical position.
Although it is individual care and education, the program of the mini kindergarten is comparable to that for preschool education.
Children do not only play but a quality education is also guaranteed - from the beginning to the preparation for school benches we teach English.
The class is equipped not only with imaginative toys and games but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of small children in society creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can control their child at any time and not have the stress of a delay to pick up the children from a school far from the parents’ workplace.
Parents use their working hours in the most productive way.
No wonder a natural relationship of loyalty between the employee and the employer is created.
Arch.Design. has thus registered among companies that offer a bonus of choice for the recruitment of new employees and that are friendly to the family and through this program strengthens HR marketing.
The bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Take a look in the interiors of Gaudi.
The roof resembles the back of a prehistoric saurian, the staircase to a dinosaur spine and the balconies to open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Battlo house in Barcelona by architect Antoni Gaudi.
Because of its organic shapes, the house received from the locals the nickname of Maison en bone.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaic, facade reminiscent of scales and everywhere of curves, this is all that is popular for the Art Nouveau of Antoni Gaudi.
The front facade of the house unfolds its dream lines, its pleasant colors and textures that recall nature and animals.
During a more detailed observation we see the geometry, the rhythm and the order thought with precision.
In the night the facade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the impression of gloss of colors is reinforced.
The winding and twisting of the shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measurement.
The wood copies in waves the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, eyelet and slats.
The Battlo house that stands in the Eixample district in the shopping street Passeig de Gracia at the number. 43, was born from the construction of a house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction was carried out for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a wealthy entrepreneur, first insisted on the demolition of the old construction and the construction of another brand new one but quickly accepted Gaudi's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a multi-dwelling house was not thought by Gaudi alone.
Architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It is precisely on his project that the decorations were born for an apartment of representation of the owner of the building and the use of the mosaic for the facade.
For the facade also worked other artists and creators.
The joint work for the plans of the Casa Battlo house began with a successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of the house of Gaudi Casa Mila and the Guell Park in which there are other works of Gaudi.
The locals dubbed the house hot just after it was finished because of its organic shapes "the Bone House".
Others, given the specific window opening mechanism called it "the bailout house".
It is said that at the top of the construction there is a sword similar to that of Saint George the patron of Catalonia.
Other elements of sculpture of the construction contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudi has designed for the house a unique system in its central heating time, with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
Their 45-degree tilt seems odd.
During the creation Gaudi did not respect the construction guidelines of the time and did not allow itself to be hindered by them.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained from the city the building permit, knowing, of course, that the data on the reconstruction plans was so vague that two years later during the finishing of the city council was horrified and asked for modifications.
It was not, for example, for members of the city council that the pillars of the construction encroached on the public sidewalk.
There was never any modification, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the call of the city Josep Battlo asked (and obtained satisfaction) permission to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a shared living room and on the third a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey house is shared by a staircase through which access is reached to an independent roof terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of the reconstruction and their replacement by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the living rooms and the high society can communicate comfortably or limit the private space for more intimate maintenance.
The house with the reconstruction of Gaudi has received in addition to new facades a non-traditional roof and two floors in addition.
Gaudi's play with light is also impressive, blue and white glass tiles with which the inner courtyard is decorated and with skylights.
The two-colored game gives maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was simply enough to bet on the principle that white reflects more than the dark that on the contrary absorbs the sun’s rays.
The Casa Battlo house, which was registered in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund, can be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and splendid apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous designer.
They continued the visits because they found that this is a lucrative business and they expanded the scope of visits to common areas and attic including the roof terraces.
The entrance ticket to the monument is really cheap and costs 16.50 euros; students, retirees, groups and tourist card holders have 20 percent off.
The sum is still above the entrance fee to Gaudi's other constructions in the city.
If you want to feel the actual atmosphere of the house with its fantastic turrets, you must quickly find a comrade among the inhabitants of the building and completely visit the house.
