Viscoelastic foams are used not only for mattresses but also for health products, such as special cushions for feet that relieve legs and venous system.
Czech manufacturers use EucathermC or Twinsaver or of the same type.
Devices to track people are increasingly in demand by parents who want to monitor their children.
Fear for their child is leading more and more people to think about watching them through a GPS.
The system, set up at the beginning to search for cars can just as well be used to trace the movement of people and help for some cases such as that of little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as big as a matchbox but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka moved a large number of people and they began to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
“We are trying to tell everyone that this is not about espionage but only about another way to reduce the likelihood that there will be another tragedy,” said Petr Pilin of MAcro Weil, which is one of the suppliers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting it in the bag of a person who is not aware, but I have not yet encountered such cases."
“The majority of people are customers who actually buy the product for safety reasons,” Pilin adds.
According to him, children should always know for what purposes the "box" is used and how to use it in case of emergency.
The child psychologist, Dana Bockova, draws attention that if the child does not want to carry on him a thing of this type, he will get rid of it.
“And even the little ones can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something on purpose when they don’t want to be under control.”
“Mobile phones, which can cut themselves like these tracking devices, have already led parents to long-standing expectations,” Bockova says.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in case of aggression is very questionable.
"If it's a prepared abduction, the author will do everything to ensure that the child does not have an electronic device that can locate him."
“Currently, it’s the phone.”
"As soon as the tracking equipment develops, they (the criminals) will also look for them because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign."
“In such cases criminals will always be ahead of the police,” the psychologist said.
She admits that such devices can help during an assault not prepared by a pedophile.
According to Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, says having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an assault.
"The device may be parameterized in such a way that it is in regular emission after a determined period."
"In the event that the device is destroyed, the last position of the person concerned remains."
“The more expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately signals the position of the person who slipped and finds himself in a lying position without moving,” Cech said.
According to him the so-called smart mobile phones that are equipped with a navigation system, can offer a comparable service after having formatted it with a special software.
The problem with current tracing systems is that it is either a device similar to those worn as a pendant the size of a matchbox or the smallest telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina of the company Macro Weil, that is why tests are being conducted to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the potential attacker will not be able to recognize the tracking device."
“Or he will realize it after a while, which will have given the police a little more time,” he added.
Whether the tracing device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as to trace cars.
This is a combination of systems for acquiring a position using GPS (which is commonly used in autonavigation) and a function of a mobile phone that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
