Households will pay an extra of a hundred crowns monthly for housing.
From January, households will have to pay extra not only for all types of energy but also for water and sanitation, heating supplies and in some places rents will also increase.
Families will have to pull from their wallets up to a hundred crowns monthly more than now.
Electricity increases by 4.6 percent, gas is almost 2 percent more expensive, in some localities you will have to pay up to a tenth more for water supply and in many places central heating supplies will also be more expensive.
The increase in electricity is expected to be around for households in apartments the 100 crowns annually more than at present.
However, all suppliers have lowered electricity prices given the significant development in encouraging the manufacture of renewable energy, including photovoltaic batteries.
The gas increases moderately but of course at a time when people need it most to heat and therefore have the greatest consumption.
We can also count a hundred more crowns.
Although electricity and gas are increasing throughout the Czech Republic, the change in the price of central heating differs from city to city.
It is mainly the largest municipalities that plan the price increase.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Kraloce will pay from January for central heating almost 50 more crowns per month, Libérec families will pay more than 1000 kronor annually.
For the inhabitants of Prague is preparing an increase of 9 percent for water and sanitation in the event that the city increases infrastructure rents.
If the rents do not change the Pragues will pay an additional 6.8 percent.
The price in Prague will still be among the lowest compared to the whole country.
In North Bohemia, where prices are already among the highest, water and sanitation are rising by 7.4 percent.
Rent prices will increase for example significantly in the 450 thousand apartments for rent from January, that is to say at the end of the regulation.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns almost 2500 apartments in Usti nad Labem, has decided to increase up to 100 percent.
Those who disagree with the new rent increase will be brought to court by the company.
The regulated rents that people pay in nearly 300 thousand apartments could increase next year by 10 percent.
Czech children get drunk with rum and fernet. Beer is no longer fashionable and acts very slowly.
Fernet, rum, vodka and exceptionally also the best brand of whisky are stolen from parents.
These are drinks that most often bring those who get drunk, who are not yet fifteen years old, in the hands of the doctor.
Children who are treated in hospital for reoffending are no exception.
This is the result of the experience of physicians who encounter cases similar to the admissions of the children's departments of hospitals.
"Beers or wines are no longer fashionable because it takes time to be drunk."
“The trend is really strong alcohols,” said Pravo Ludek Pelikan, head of the children’s department of Horovice Hospital in central Bohemia.
"When they manage to steal a bottle from Dad in the closet, it's sometimes Wisky but it's the fernet and the vodka that prevails.
“Vodka has this advantage that they can mix it with fruit juice and so do not smell it,” explains the head of the department.
Eva Jurinova, a spokesman for the Motol Hospital, is also right.
"In general, it's rum or fernet."
"Today it is the alcohol in fashion especially in elementary schools."
"In some cases, it was about slivovice that they brought home," Jurinova added.
According to the Head of Department Pélikan, seeing drunken children aged thirteen to fourteen years for hospital admissions is a normal phenomenon.
Before working in Horovice since last year, he was in Motol where he practiced ten years in pediatrics where ambulances brought schoolchildren from the wide areas completely drunk.
"A young girl was hospitalized in this way four times
"She started her career at the age of twelve when she was brought in with 3.5 per thousand alcohol in the blood with in addition a mixture with ecstasy," the doctor described the particularly important case.
"She was at the Holesovice Exhibition Centre at a party."
"What's interesting is that it didn't appear weird to the mother that his daughter is away 48 hours," said the Department's director.
It is precisely the disinterestedness of parents or their extraordinary tolerance in the face of the fact that their offspring indulge in drinking that are the main cause of the development of children's alcoholism.
According to the specialists, however, we do not speak of the dependence, in its strict sense, for children.
"Under the alcoholic term we hear a chronic addiction to alcohol of several years with all the phenomena that result from it but that we do not find in children."
“In those who use recurrent alcohol, it is rather a significantly unfavorable socio-family back-ground,” explained the Head of Department Pélikan.
According to spokeswoman Jurinova, about forty drunken children were hospitalized this year until mid-November in the pediatric clinic in Motol.
Only cases with a serious intoxication requiring hospitalization are integrated into the statistics.
Children who are drunk who are after emergency care taken home by parents or police are not counted.
In addition to the cases of children who sit and drink a bottle of alcohol after school, according to Pelikan, there are three seasonal waves with which we can count: the day of the witches, the holy Sylvestre and the end of the school year.
"Either they drink out of spite after poor results or on the contrary they celebrate the beginning of the holidays."
"Of course I experienced on Witch Day an admission of 7 drunken children at once," Pélikan said.
The drunken child who spent the night in the hospital in detoxification under medical supervision is paradoxically in a better position than the one who returned home and suffers the day after the "whim of wood".
Morning headaches caused by dehydration and lack of glucose are eliminated by an infusion of glucose and nutrients that the body needs.
"They are for this reason better off since they spend a great evening and then a sweet awakening and nothing hurts them."
“They’re only amazed at where they are,” Pélikan adds, knowing that from time to time it spoils the good mood of patients at least with the grade to pay for their care.
Transport by ambulance and intensive care bed hospitalization can range into tens of thousands of crowns.
“From time to time, I applied this as a means of education by counting to these children how much their drunkenness cost and that they could spend the whole summer in seasonal work to pay off a single evening,” added Pelikan.
However, according to him, health insurance companies in their declining managements, which should recover from parents the care-related burdens, do not deal with cases of drunken children.
Two L-159 aircraft are for the first time in foreign hands in Spain.
Two L-159 of the five in total, for which the Ministry of Defense exchanged Casa C-295M transport aircraft, took off Tuesday for Seville in Spain where the aircraft manufacturer Casa-EADS is headquartered.
This is the first time that such aircraft have become the property of anyone other than the Czech army.
However, they have been abroad in the context of exercises or demonstration flights.
These are the two-seater versions of the L-159T1 which were until now in service in the Czech army and were in flight condition.
The remaining three devices are single-seater versions of the L-159.
These are currently stationed at Aero Vodochody and the commercial intermediary - the firm Omnipol - took them into account last week.
According to Jan Pejsek of the press department of the Ministry of Defense, the physical departure of the aircraft from Vodochody is currently unknown.
“The L-159 single-seater aircraft planned for the exchange have been taken on long-stored aircraft without causing additional charges or investment for the Ministry of Defence.”
“The two-seater L-159 T1s were traded in the state,” Pejsek said.
He added that the army would not remain without a two-seater since the ministry signed an agreement worth 200 million crowns in May 2009 for the department to convert four unused L-159 single-seaters into two two-seater aircraft.
The army took delivery of the first aircraft in July, the second being scheduled for delivery at the end of this year.
According to Pejsek EADS has committed to introducing aircraft into the equipment of some Alliance countries.
"In the contract it is clearly stated that the one who takes L-159 aircraft into account is EADS and that they will be used to train pilots from NATO member countries."
"This is therefore the case of the one who takes into account determining how to achieve this," Pejsek said.
Hospodarske noviny announced some time ago that the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
The exchange of five L-159s for a Casa aircraft and the purchase of three other aircraft for 3.5 billion crowns was endorsed last year by the government of Mirek Topomanek.
The Ministry of Defence did not issue a tender and contacted EADS directly.
The Directorate of Defence argued that the exchange ensures a future export of the L-159 abroad.
The Czech army bought 72 aircraft from Aero Vodochody and only uses 24 of them, wanting to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa aircraft will likely have legal implications.
However, the European Commission has lodged a complaint against the Czech Ministry of Defence with the European Court of Justice because the aircraft should have been selected in the context of a European-wide call for tenders and in no case by contacting a manufacturer directly.
The army has already taken delivery of three Casa aircraft, the last one is expected to arrive at Prague Kbely airport in two weeks.
A longer index than the ring finger is a sign of low risk of cancer
Men who have the longer index than the ring finger are at lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
It may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
“Our findings show that relative finger length serves as a simple prostate cancer risk test, especially for men before the age of 60,” said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could thus help determine which men should undergo the prostate cancer test, including combining with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009 she followed with her colleagues in Great Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the right-hand index shorter than the ring finger.
For them as for the 19 percent of those who had the fingers of the same length, we found the same probability of prostate cancer.
For those with the longer index than the ring finger, however, the risk fell to 33 percent, for men before age 60 the decrease in risk reached 87 percent.
The ratio of length of the two mentioned fingers - formed during the prenatal period - indicates in particular different levels of sex hormones to which the child in the uterus is exposed.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research had shown that it is precisely testosterone that helps in the development of prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, said for CTK that he is aware of this study but that it does not seem to him, it seems, that the relationship between finger length and cancer is "completely demonstrated".
