The master glacier Luciano Ferrari first explains to the participants the ideal characteristics of the perfect ice cream.
Is decisive not only the good flavor, but also the silky flexibility and the right consistency.
However, Luciano does not forget during the formation the icing on the cake of the national superstructure and, in general, from the south: "The Italian ice is simply the best: and then it still retains a hell of a dose of romanticism."
The first step in manufacturing seems quite simple.
Luciano pours the basic ingredients, such as milk, cream, milk powder, sugar and stabilizers into a large blender that heats everything to 85 degrees thanks to an electronic program, and then cools immediately to four degrees.
He then opens a tap installed on the machine: there comes out a white cream of pasteurized base, foundation of all kinds of milk ice cream.
The trainer is immediately beset by question: Is it possible to make ice using only natural substances without a stabilizer?
How can we give free rein to the personal pleasure of experimentation?
M. Luciano warns against the fact of being misled by the spirit of the time.
The one who speaks only of ice creams "made from natural ingredients", has perhaps used stabilizers despite this: most often a natural product, for example guar seed flour obtained from guar bean.
It is obviously possible to make ice without using a stabilizer, only it must be sold within 24 hours, otherwise it collapses and the customer will not crunch anything but ice granules.
Some changes in the base mass are permitted.
This becomes more exciting with aromas.
The master Luciano establishes the difference between the ingredients that one acquires in the fruit or confectionery department of the supermarket.
In addition, there is powder and pasta.
"Suppliers will all try to give you dozens of flavored ingredients."
"However, you should just try."
Either in fruit sorbet recipes with sugar and fresh fruit.
Either in ice creams made from the white base mass which, by adding eggs to it becomes a yellow cream and is, when added cocoa powder, the basis of all possible chocolate desserts.
Now, all participants in the course must switch to using the ice machines.
Luciano invites them from time to time to make four kinds of ice cream: vanilla, chocolate, mocha and hazelnut with or without eggs in the base mass, with more or less vanilla aroma or other natural ingredients.
The different kinds of fruit ice creams are also subject to the same experience.
More aromatic substances, no more fruit purees: from the point of view of taste, this is not absolutely better.
Hazelnut ice cream does not necessarily have the taste of nuts, when it is composed largely of hazelnuts.
Kiwi ice cream, very popular, is made from the group using more fruit, less water and a little less stabilizer.
“Only a balanced blend correctly picks up the taste of an ice cream,” says Luciano.
The manufacture of ice is a calculation exercise: if we use peach puree with a lot of sugar, it is necessary that the amount of sugar be reduced in the basic recipe.
A sugar supplement is required for lemon ice cream.
Luciano presents a device with which he determines the sugar content of the different types of fruit (the winemakers use it to measure the degree of Oechsle in the grape must).
Fortunately, the tables make the calculations easier.
The manufacture of ice no longer requires, as in the past, so much physical intervention.
It is not only the automatic manufacturing machine of the base mass that helps.
There is also an apparatus in which the ice mixture available is simultaneously beats to make it smooth and brought back to negative temperatures.
Despite all the automations, slight breakdowns are not excluded.
The Brazilian Gustavo smears himself with fruit puree from head to toe and, thus, splashes his fellow students when the control of the colossal mixing bowl escapes him.
Master Luciano is of the opinion that an "incident like this may occur during each course: it is only a matter of time."
