The whole extent of the ravages is obvious when you walk through the mangrove marshes crossed by streams.
Instead of clear water, the motorboat splits crading brown water. Whoever plunges his hand out of it all covered with oil.
The roots of small mangroves emerge from the ground like licorice sticks. The isolated palms sadly hang their palms.
We search in vain for the clouds of birds, as we usually encounter in wetlands: As long as the outboard engine stops, a ghostly silence falls on this paradise of old that resembles a gas station by the smell it gives off.
"What's happening here is war on the environment," says Mr. Celestine Akpobari with a sad air: "Our life is characterized by a permanent danger when it comes to health."
The comparison of wars is made.
The area where the Ogoni live has been a besieged battlefield for decades: More than 60 years ago, the first European explorers entered here; the first resistance was organized in the 1980s by the writer Ken Saro-Wiwa. This one was executed later. In 1993, the Shell Group had to halt its production activities in this region because they had become very dangerous for its employees.
Even today, the return to the country Ogoni is forbidden to this company: While more than 2 million barrels of black gold are daily pumped thanks to more than 5000 boreholes and 7000 kilometers of oil pipelines throughout the Delta region, three times large like Switzerland, the oil fields of the Ogoni country are untapped, because the situation is too unstable for this oil group.
Every few hundred meters stand in the water steel trestles as strange sculptures: We very affectionately refer to "Christmas trees" the heads of boreholes.
They are up to 50 years old, most are eaten away by corrosion up to the marker.
Akpobari believes that a drilling head of this nature breaks from time to time in pieces, because a constant flow of crude oil flows into the water.
According to experts' estimates, more than two billion litres have poured into the ecosystem in 50 years: Every year, the amount of oil equivalent to that which flowed into the sea during the accident of the supertank tanker "Exxon Valdez" 21 years ago off Alaska, one of the largest environmental disasters in human history.
Who should bear responsibility for persistent environmental pollution? the answer to this question divides the actors.
For the Shell Group, the sabotage and siphoning of pipelines is responsible for more than 90 percent of the pollution. Environmentalists, for their part, consider the explosions of drilling heads and perforated oil pipelines to be the main causes.
In 2008, U.S. researcher Richard Steiner criticized the Shell group for applying essentially less stringent safety standards in Nigeria than anywhere else in the world: Only the rate of pipe failures is "still much higher than alleys".
Some shapes emerge from the mangroves to a place that, seen from a distance, looks like an abandoned workshop, full of cambouis and installed in the open air: They are completely naked and covered with cambouis up to the neck.
A fire sparkles under one of the many barrels that sometimes connected to the pipes, sometimes scattered without pattern on the site must be repeated: a small clandestine refinery.
We heat the crude oil in the barrel for several hours, says Michael, the team leader.
Initially, gasoline enters a container through pipes, then at the end of the pipe of the kerosene drops fall and diesel is finally obtained.
This is how Michael and his four collaborators produce four 300-liter diesel drums daily: "It brings us 34 000 Naira", about 22 dollars.
Delta residents are leveraging the chronic fuel shortage in the largest oil-producing country in Black Africa.
Nigeria has only one refinery.
Illegal refiners can sell at a price cheaper than the ridiculously low price of just 40 cents of Euro per litre of Diesel: Because they acquire their raw material for free.
It is offered by the "protectors" who put the network of pipelines into pierce throughout the country of Ogoni. According to experts, the country loses at least 16 million litres of crude oil throughout the Niger Delta.
Only a small, insignificant part of the provisionally stored raw material is illegally purified: The organized crime networks that also include high-ranking politicians and military personnel, charge the lion’s share in tankers and sell it to the world market.
The activist Akpobari considers that the debate on whether to attribute the environmental disaster or rather the subversive activities to the population or the lax mode of production is purely academic.
“If oil companies were not perceived as intruders and if the foundations of fishermen’s lives were not so deeply destroyed, there would be no sabotage, nor illegal theft and refineries.”
But, in the meantime, the Ogoni's relations especially with Shell have deteriorated so much that it was only a question of the withdrawal of the group. "Maybe operators with other nationalities, such as the Chinese, will prove to be better."
So Michael gets nervous.
"It's high time you got running," announces the robust oil worker.
"Soldiers can appear at any time."
If the illegal refiners are surprised by the special units of the armed forces, they will certainly not be arrested, but at most they will offer them bribes.
Even soldiers mainly from the north of the country intend to enjoy raw material like all Nigerians.
"From every point of view, this damn thing has brought down our country very low," Akpori regrets.
