Is the film Splatter an artificial film?
Director Nicolas Winding Refn explores the limits of the ancient genre through his film, "Walhalla Rising", the fighter's epic.
What audience could the Danish director Nicolas Winding Refn think of when he turned "Walhalla Rising"?
A Viking warrior (Mads Mikkelsen) possessing only one eye is taken prisoner; he frees himself from his executioner and, with almost supernatural strength, eliminates his opponents one after the other. This seems ideal for young male spectators looking for a bloody action, precisely because our hero uses brutal assassination methods. When he is in a bad mood, he tears the intestines of his enemies without waiting for them to be dead.
On the other hand, until the end of the film, the blind does not say any word about its real name. Even the other characters let out, at most, at the bend of one or two sentences a few cries of appalling agony.
Otherwise, we say nothing and we feast in the incredibly beautiful mountainous landscape of Scotland that is the setting of the Viking universe, about a thousand years ago.
This would be ideal plus mature filmmakers with an interest in existentialism and excellent travelling.
When a film targets several target groups, it is a shame that they are mutually exclusive.
The director Winding Refn is considered, since the publication of "Pusher", his trilogy relating to the drug trafficker fierce and full of style, as a kind of Danish Quentin Tarantinon, but he refuses to bring a little more mood to the mainstream or introduce a little less brutality to the cinema of art and essay.
Most art cinema supporters must experience horror in the face of the brain that spreads all around and the intestines.
Fans of action films die of boredom, when the blind embarks, for reasons that can be freely interpreted, with a group of violent Christian missionaries in a ship bound for Jerusalem; they are drowned for an eternity by calm and mist before the crew arrives in America and continues to remain silent.
It is not surprising then that "Walhalla Rising" has not found any film distributor in Germany and that it exists only in DVD format.
It is mainly because of the magnificent images of misery that has earned some attention, but also because the image of a thrilling film, from time to time, hides behind a pretentious and bloody appearance.
It is not about dialogues in this film, nor a coherent action, everything is atmosphere, a feverish dream transformed into a film.
The spectator cannot escape it.
Refn barely gives him a moment of relaxation and slowly cuts his throat with frigid images and a gloomy soundtrack, but above all with an elusive hatred that springs from the hearts of the characters.
Only a young blonde boy, who stands faithfully by the blind, preserves a certain innocence, all the others are animated by anger.
More than anything, the blind hero whose mobiles are never known, but who returns from hell at any time to fight enemies and temporarily allies by turning into a warrior, is perhaps sent from the devil himself.
It represents rot, but perhaps also, just for those who are, anyway, rotten.
"Walhalla Rising" is an enigmatic film that can be hated or admired, which aims to annoy, enthusiasm and astonishment.
A traumatic experience.
Mysterious earthworks
The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) has new indications for a nuclear program developed by Syria.
But this country refuses to take a position on this subject, much less to submit to the controls of the agency.
On the night of 5 to 6 September 2007 around midnight, at least four Israeli F-15 I fighter jets attacked a mysterious cubic-shaped building on Syrian territory.
It is located on the bank of the euphrates; the largest city located nearby is 30 kilometers away: it is Dair as-Sur.
Its name appears in IAEA documents, because it is about the reactor that Syria has built with the help of North Korea in parallelepiped stone, hidden in a valley marked by the absence of electric current.
According to a briefing by the U.S. intelligence services, the CIA, dating back to the end of April 2008, the current reactor, known as the nearby locality, el-Kibar, would be well able to produce plutonium, which would make it possible to manufacture atomic weapons.
However, this technique has been valid since the 1950’s.
The CIA showed a presentation video featuring blurred satellite images.
Through computer-aided animation, it indicated the likely location of each component of the reactor before the destruction of the plant, which represents a miniature copy of the North Korean model of the Yongbyon nuclear power plant.
In addition, she presented the photos showing the building located nearby, or even the interior of it.
It appears that the reactor was about to be put into operation, but it was not yet equipped with fuel bars.
Today, more than three years after the Israeli bombing, there is barely more information than at the time, and even, over time, the mystery is becoming more and more thicker.
Former President of the United States George W. Bush recently revealed in his memoirs that before the attack, the CIA was certainly sure that Syria had built a reactor in el-Kibar, but had little evidence showing this country was developing "an active nuclear weapons program."
Some intelligence agents in Europe prefer to be more cautious about it and only talk about an "alleged reactor", even if they consider the CIA's presentation to be "plausible."
They lack hard evidence, as well as the IAEA.
Asked how he makes sure he is dealing with a nuclear reactor, a senior diplomat from the United Nations gave only a laconic response in the summer by saying that the IAEA had "sufficient documents to ask questions."
The Syrians certainly hastily removed the rubble from the "unused military building" and proceeded with a methodical flattening of the ground.
However, in June 2008, a team of IAEA experts led by former chief inspector Oli Heinonen, discovered traces of uranium produced by the men in el-Kibar.
In addition, the IAEA has received satellite images from commercial providers through a member state showing the moment that directly followed the attack, and it appears that the attacks are more eloquent than those presented by the CIA.
However, these photos are not available on the market because the anonymous sponsor, perhaps Israel, acquired them exclusively.
It is therefore impossible for the IAEA to establish their authenticity objectively.
Syria has always assured that it has never carried out a secret atomic program and that it has not built a reactor.
Damascus maintains that the uranium found at the site comes from weapons used by Israel.
But the IAEA rejected this argument after the particle analysis, calling it unbelievable.
Since that time, Damascus has refused any discussion about it, as well as about satellite images.
In addition, Syria does not allow the controllers to carry out a second inspection at the el-Kibar site and refuses access to the rubble of the building destroyed by the bomb.
But even Israel remains a stubborn silence.
Confirming the official position, Ehud Olmert, then Prime Minister-in-Office at the time of the attack, recently said: "We will never comment on this."
Thus, the investigation of this case has been going on since June 2008 without a result and "is becoming more and more a serious problem of the Agency's credibility", as acknowledged by a senior Western diplomat in service at the IAEA headquarters in Vienna, finally it is a serious violation of the Treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons.
The IAEA considers that progress must be made to clarify the existence of the three other facilities that must have "functional relation" to the alleged reactor.
To date, inspectors have not indicated which facilities it is here, what their function is or what they are suspected of containing.
According to information published by the newspaper "Süddeutsche Zeitung", they are known within the IAEA respectively under the names of Marj as-Sultan, Masyaf and Iskandariayah also named after the neighboring cities.
The Independent Institute for Science and International Security in Washington identified these localities and discovered on satellite images a complex near Masyaf that would most likely be one of the suspicious objects.
It may be in or directly from a military base, which is exactly why Syria refuses access to IAEA inspectors for the three sites.
In Vienna, it is claimed that the Syrians fear that the inspection group will in fact be spies who would be sent on behalf of the United States by the IAEA to spy on military installations.
In fact, it is intelligence provided by U.S. secret agents that attracts the attention of nuclear inspectors.
The IAEA has information, including satellite photos, indicating that vehicles have shuttled between the three sites and the stone parallelepiped to transport substances.
A senior Western diplomat said in Vienna that at least one of the facilities could "serve fuel production."
It would have "no indication of sensitive activities" such as the enrichment and reprocessing of uranium; processes that are essential for the production of atomic weapons.
This type of reactor certainly works thanks to non-enriched uranium.
Nevertheless, there are plausible assumptions about the following fundamental questions: where uranium should have come from and where the plutonium needed to make the bomb should have been separated later.
It is unclear whether the rubble, which could hide traces of high value, were stored at all three sites.
When the hundreds of trucks loaded with land have disappeared, no one will have information about the place of storage of the rubble.
For the IAEA, it is unlikely that Syria had the al-Tibni salt mine examined in 1998, located only a few kilometers from el-Kibar, on the other side of the Euphrates River, to see if it may be suitable for the storage of radioactive waste.
By recently analyzing satellite photos on behalf of the famous Jane's Intelligence Review magazine, the former IAEA inspector, Mr. Robert Kelley has established a link between these and the reactor in question.
Satellite photos show, however, that Syria has undertaken earthworks at the three suspicious sites and moved huge containers when the IAEA began requiring access to these locations.
It may be a coincidence, but it did not help to rule out suspicions.
In the diplomatic circles, it is said that the IAEA has spent several months developing a plan for inspections to be carried out there. This plan was to allow Syria to preserve possible military secrets. Only the time invested shows what great interest the inspectors have in this case.
Meanwhile, Damascus has also ignored this proposal.
A year ago, if Western diplomats in Vienna had not reported the destruction of the reactor, the emergency would not be reported for this case, says, for example, Glyn Davies, the U.S. ambassador who has been talking for a few months about what is known as special inspections, one of the most powerful ways the Atomic Agency has to implement its controls.
The Director of the IAEA, Mr. Yukiya Amano, who had to offer these inspections, has already spoken of "an option to which I am open in the future", but he still hesitates.
This means entails an enormous risk: on the one hand, it requires a majority in the IAEA Board of Governors and many of the 35 countries represented there have no desire to see the situation escalate.
On the other hand, like this diplomat who gives to reflect: "Would it serve, if in the end they find nothing"
