Can civility bring the divides closer together?
After a campaign marked by invective and negativity, a minimum of civility broke out in Washington this week.
Is this a warning sign of genuine bipartisan cooperation forward or an illusory moment before the swift return to partisan struggle in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no breakthrough on the major issues that need to be addressed during the “lame duck” session.
But obviously, there was at least a polite discussion about the differences of the two sides as well as the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points empty of partisan point rating.
Wednesday’s public meeting of the committee on the president’s deficit was equally civilized, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created a mutual respect transcendent of the ideological divide; but which, however, further divides the members.
This is barely enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has come.
Both sides are now in a period of trial and mutual testing for signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
That is why Tuesday’s meeting and subsequent comments from participants revealed a minimum of demands or charges.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and too deep to suggest a rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxation, spending, health care or rights, both parties remain miles away.
However, the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
“There’s no doubt that things have changed in the tone,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official, now alongside the Center for Ethical and Public Policy.
"It's inevitable after the election.
Elections arouse partisan passions and then they fade.
That's good."
On some issues, including those on the agenda of the "lame duck" session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of that.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of them, either permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is possible on the extension of unemployment benefits, if only because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favor of tax cuts for the rich, while denying unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, more optimism hangs over a possible agreement on the issues raised during the session on the "lame duck", with the ratification of the "New START" pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warned that fruitful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the "lame duck" session would not necessarily lead to a better understanding between the two parties when the 112th Congress met in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
“Once the things that need to be done will be done, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations,” he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared skepticism that civility would lead to genuine cooperation.
“I consider most of what happens between today and 2012 as a pre-show or shadow-boxing compared to the main event of 2012, he said.
The reasons for this are closely related to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters present at the tea who contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know they must try to live up to their promises to cut public spending and repeal the new health care law.
These partisan positions are already clear in the initial responses to the recommendations of the deficit commission, which include reforming the tax code and raising certain taxes, raising the retirement age and cutting spending.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles chose one of Washington’s toughest tasks and, in their view, imposed the deficit issue on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes on the 18-member commission to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they struggled to reach that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the elected representatives of the group; which suggests that there is on tax issues, at least today, few reasons or willingness to compromise.
Galston is planning two phases in the fights between the White House and the Republicans of Congress.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan clashes, given that Republicans are challenging Obama in terms of budget, taxes and health care; and then being followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of the change?
Public opinion.
There is ample evidence that, despite the partisan spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see both parties work together.
If the confrontation leads to a deadlock, as in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the reaction of the public.
Whoever is judged in loss will have to change course and find compromises.
But it would be an optimistic view.
The partisan spirit and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990’s and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and the Republicans of Congress than there were then between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, the activists of both parties see 2010 as a simple prelude to a more substantial election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility exposed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on the part of both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
