The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, if not rather frequent in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, the rules not written, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate that appeared in the case related is due to the fact that this has had as protagonist a team of the entity of Real Madrid (which in its anthem displays the nobility and honor and which on past occasions has fined its players for similar acts) and the dramatization orchestrated, it seems, by Mourinho, which adds one more episode to its dilated history.
In any case, the debate asks whether this type of conduct does not expressly prohibit by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, that is to say, if with these actions we commit a fraud of law; because, in fact, they are respectful actions with the sports regulations, but seem to evade its meaning.
The question is to examine the type of harm they cause to the sportsmanship.
One of the properties that includes sportsmanship is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions has not been endangered, that is, there has been no violent play.
Another of these properties to which we allude with the correct game is to prevent the team of the infractor players from benefiting unfairly from the opposing team, which is not the case either.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not agree to what is normally characterized as cheating or fraud of the law, because its violation of the rules was not carried out in secret to try to avoid the penalty, but their action has precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalty of the referee.
They were waiting and they gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is the type of advantage that offenders get from the intentional faults examined.
Here it seems necessary to find that we do not put in a situation of disadvantage to the rival and we do not get an advantage in the same match either, because obviously the result of the action presupposes leaving their own team with fewer players.
And this is not a useful strategy for the next match either, because the club could not count on these players.
Obviously the advantage is that the players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that can threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, because the team could be eliminated all of a sudden and apart from that, with this action the players perform a sanction match and move on to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of the boxes occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, climbing the ladder is not so clear that it is an advantage.
Ultimately, these actions are not contrary to the sportsmanship, from which is still part of the taking of strategic decisions that promote the maximum profit of what the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not act to avoid the application of the penalty (this would indeed be a clear case of fraud of the law), otherwise they chose rather the time in which they submitted to it.
They made a strategic decision without thwarting the penalty or running away from it.
Even if the boundary between genius and the fraud of the law is diffuse, on this occasion I think we had a clear case of genius.
The controversy, it seems to me, appears because of two factors: because there have been two self-evictions and because of the way to transmit the director to provoke them.
The evil provoked by the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as aesthetic.
