The European Union is changing the rules for obtaining a visa
Individuals must go to the Visa Applicant Service Centres prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost of waiting time will be reduced.
From 10 January 2011 the procedure for processing visas at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to report to the Visa Applicant Service Centres (VSAs) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
CSA staff will take the applicant's biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for aspirants, including the following:
The total cost to process the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to obtain an appointment, another payment for the visa processing and another for the mail service to deliver the document.
The aspirant will make a single payment that will cover the three services.
The current tariff will remain the same: the equivalent of 140 dollars for a tourist visa, 150 dollars in the case of visas with application (includes visas for temporary workers) and 390 dollars for visas of traders and investors.
Individuals who wish to renew their visa will not be required to attend an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only report to the nearest CSA where they will present the documents and take their fingerprints.
Because the biometric information will be taken in the CSA, applicants who wish a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will stay less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants at the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service rate of 26 dollars.
For more information on the new procedure for applying for the visa, visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
