A global plan to renovate lighting
The UN proposed yesterday in Cancún a plan to renovate domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to achieve a reduction in greenhouse gases (GHGs) that accounts for almost a third of the additional reduction that must be achieved to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in the wake of the major concrete projects that the UN hopes to have adopted in Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments by industrialized countries.
According to the plan filed yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs that still monopolize 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by compact fluorescent bulbs or, better, by light-emitting diode bulbs (LEDs or "LEDs" in English), most of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GHGs emitted on the planet to illuminate humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions of the global car fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitting countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, have embarked on voluntary reduction plans that are expected to increase overall GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to subtract from this balance sheet another 5 Gt to manage to stabilize by 2020 the rise of the climate to 2 degrees centigrade to avoid that it becomes out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy dissipates in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, produces light.
With compact fluorescent bulbs, the energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, we reduce this energy need by twice again.
The compact fluorescent bulbs last on average from 6000 to 10 000 hours.
The new LED light bulbs, like those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week - this company participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25 000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent light bulb, which gives an idea of the possible saving with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These brand new bulbs can also work with rheostats in addition to emitting very little heat.
And they contain no mercury.
Several specialists have shown reservations about compact fluorescent light bulbs because they contain mercury and that they should be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers put in place instructions.
But, the report says, the main source of mercury emission on the planet is not the compact fluorescent light bulb, but rather coal-fired power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce wasted electricity in incandescent light bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25 000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report details the gains that each country would make through this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars a year in electricity purchases and eight million tonnes of CO2, equivalent to 3.5 thermal power plants, which would cost it 2.5 billion.
