The unemployment rate in France within the meaning of the International Labour Office (ILO) remained stable at 9.3% in metropolitan France (9.7% by counting the overseas departments), show the provisional seasonally adjusted data (CVS) published Thursday by INSEE.
The number of unemployed is 2.631 million in metropolitan France.
Data for the second quarter were confirmed at 9.3% of the working population in metropolitan France and 9.7% with the overseas departments.
Over a year, the unemployment rate is up 0.1 percentage points.
More broadly, 3.4 million people in metropolitan France did not work in the third quarter but wanted to work, whether or not they were available within two weeks to work and whether or not they were looking for a job.
The situation of young people on the labour market has deteriorated further, with a further increase in the unemployment rate, increased to 24.2% in metropolitan France (+ 0.9 points over three months, +0.5 points over a year) and 25% by including the overseas departments.
In the third quarter, 637 000 young people aged 15 to 24 were unemployed within the meaning of ILO.
The elderly experienced a slight increase in unemployment, to 6.4% in metropolitan France (+0.2 points over three months as well as over a year), i.e. 482,000 people aged 50 or over, and 6.6% with the French overseas departments.
Only the 25-49 year olds benefited from a stability of unemployment in the third quarter, at 8.3% in metropolitan France (-0.1 point over three months, +0.1 point over a year) and 8.8% throughout France.
