No online games for young Koreans past midnight
The South Korean government will pass a so-called "Cinderella" law that will prohibit teenagers from playing online games after midnight by blocking their access, government officials said.
A bill will be submitted to Parliament in December to ask online gaming companies to block access to these games after midnight, to young people under the age of 16, representatives of the ministries of culture and the family said.
“A lot of kids play these games all night and then have difficulty studying at school and having a normal life during the day.”
“We believe that this law is necessary to guarantee their health and their right to sleep,” Jo Rin, the minister’s official in charge of the bill, told AFP.
Online games will be available again at 6 a.m.
Companies will have one year to prepare for law enforcement, he said.
The government is also considering asking companies to limit the daily time of access to these games for young people whose parents are requesting them, the official added.
It will also make available to people who demand it free software that allows to limit the time spent on the Internet.
South Korea is one of the most "connected" countries and newspapers regularly report miscellaneous facts related to intensive Internet use.
The country is also the undisputed champion of global online gaming competitions.
In November, South Korea won four gold medals at the World Cyber Games, against 58 other nations.
