Avenged hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals itself an apparent scandal, a scandal that appears as scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs the relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level, and foreshadows a future dominated by regression.
But let's proceed in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that each file constituted by a secret service (of any nation) is composed exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only report what for months could be read in any newspaper (except those owned by Berlusconi), and Gaddafi's sinisterly cartoonish profile had long been for sketchmaking cabaret artists.
The rule that secret files should only be composed of news already known is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each book repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in previous works.
And this not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do new research (nor does it know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to occultism only believe in what they already know, and who reconfirms what they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
The same goes for the secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited-minded) the head of the secret services (otherwise he might be, what do I know, editor at Libération), who retains as true only what he recognizes.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the U.S. Embassy in Rome was sending to the State Department was the same as the one that Newsweek was publishing the week before.
So why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what any educated person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since the heads of state can call themselves or take a plane to meet at dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small performance exercises, have turned into espionage centers.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only by hypocrisy that we pretend to ignore him.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to place American diplomacy in a bad light.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker could capture the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
The scandal therefore does not put the victims in crisis as much as the "exeembrals".
But let’s come to the deep nature of what happened.
Once, in Orwell's time, one could conceive of any power like a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had been completely true since, being able to control every movement through the phone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway used and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when we demonstrate, as it happens now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control report ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
The power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as a vengeful of the citizen - can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the opportunity to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said, that a real secret is an empty secret (and empty secret can never be revealed); it is true, also, that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed a secret empty of secrecy, because belonging to the public domain; but revealing, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means to remove all power from him.
WikiLeaks did no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but made it too big on Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is obvious that in the future, states will no longer be able to put online any reserved information - this would be tantamount to publishing it on a poster stuck to the corner.
But it is also obvious that with current technologies, it is futile to hope to be able to maintain confidential reports by telephone.
Nothing is easier than to find out if and when a head of state flew and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved reports be maintained in the future?
I know that, for the moment, my prediction is science fiction and is therefore romantic, but I am obliged to imagine government agents who move discreetly in diligences with uncontrollable routes, being wearing only messages learned by heart or, at most, by hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept in a single copy in locked drawers: at the bottom, the attempt to spy on the Watergate has been less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now moving forward in crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet restored a telegraph on wire (phones).
The (analog) video cassettes had allowed film researchers to explore a step-by-step film, going back and forth and discovering all the secrets of editing, while now the (digital) CDs only allow you to jump from chapter to chapter, that is, by macroportions.
With high-speed trains, we go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, and the travels it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not extraordinary that the policy and communication techniques go back to the horse-drawn cars.
One last observation.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was going on in the secret of the embassies.
Now it is the embassies that request confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France is hacking its promises of funding
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to review the fulfilment of the promises of rapidly released financing (so-called fast-start or early financing) made by developed countries.
And the big French hacks are revealed.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged to provide US$30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has promised 7.2 billion euros over three years and France 1.26 billion euros (420 million per year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU took the big game to persuade its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: report detailing the action of its member states, press conference, large side event, distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation is appreciable and appreciated: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released 2.2 billion euros in 2010, putting it on the right track to meet its commitment of 7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look in detail, things are more complicated.
This money must be, according to the Copenhagen agreement, "new and additional", in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without being at the expense of Official Development Assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States whose procedure France blocked.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission considered the year 2009 to be a reference: international funding is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years for fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
On the other hand, France believes that the funding for "all new projects" of 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to previous years' spending or to the overall level of Official Development Assistance.
Specifically, the total amount of France’s support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to meet its commitment to “new and additional” financing...
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses their calculation method.
Some, like France, consider that 1 € loaned is equivalent to 1 € given.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
While the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to emission mitigation that are based on more efficient technologies), it is misleading to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that we give... At most, only the cost of the loan to the lending country (equivalent to an interest rate) should be counted under its liabilities.
But France has nothing to do with such a reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only EU country to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in others) meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts 1 € to satisfy its commitment, France only puts 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Nice trick!
In summary, in its fast start financing, France operates a double scam: on the one hand on the evolution of the action over time and on the other hand on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only 36.1 million euros, it manages to make it believe that it spends 420 million "new and additional" in line with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why the other Member States would continue to give if it is enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since the developing countries are not completely fooled...
The chapter of early funding is only a small, relative short-term issue, compared to all climate discussions.
But it could be another grain of sand in the huge machine that is the UNFCCC.
Hopefully this will not be the case.
In any case, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First of all, France could announce a change in its method of accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and equity with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could advance the discussions on long-term financing issues (other crucial chapter currently discussed): we will not escape the question of "additionality" or the method of accounting for loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope is therefore on the new Minister of the Environment, Ms. Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France’s fast start and its vision of “additionality” and the use of loans would be likely to increase the level of international trust needed to move forward in the discussions.
Alert to pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests in a day 81 different chemicals, according to a study published this Wednesday by the association Générations Futures (ex-Movement for rights and respect for future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "do not have a significant statistical value in view of the small number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem treated", bought between July and September the food generally consumed in four meals and a snack in one day by a child of about ten years, in the supermarkets of Oise and Paris.
These typical meals, including official recommendations - five fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 litres of water per day - as well as treats, were reviewed by laboratories looking for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, 42 of which are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances classified as carcinogenic as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (EPs), according to studies by several institutions such as the International Agency for Research on Cancer.
"Although, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each chemical substance taken individually are not exceeded, we can clearly see in our investigation that the reality of consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic and/or PE contaminants is of concern," the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three proven as certain carcinogens as well as nearly twenty residues likely to disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, planned as a snack by the study, has traces of six chemicals including a fungicide banned in France.
The same goes for Kenya's green beans, included in the lunch, on which the study detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, chopped steak, canned tuna, and even bread baguette and chewing gum were full of pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, the analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
For dinner, the salmon steak was the "richest" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the examination of the plastic plate used to warm the meal in the microwave was not exempt.
The final risk to the consumer of this "contaminant cocktails" "is probably underestimated", according to the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecology-Greens (EE-LV), for its part, proposed "facing the urgency of the situation" to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides, in order to stop "the increase in diseases of civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) reported the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
